ACUTE: A person who has the _____ form of a disorder, such as schizophrenia.
CEDILLA: In the spelling of Catalan, French, Portuguese and some other languages, a mark (¸) sometimes placed under the letter c to indicate that it is pronounced /s/ rather than /k/, as in Catalan força, French menaçant, and Portuguese almoço, and also used in various other languages to change the sounds of other letters.
CIRCUMFLEX: A diacritical mark (ˆ) placed over a vowel in the orthography or transliteration of many languages to change its pronunciation; while in some other languages over a consonant.
GRAVE: An excavation in the earth as a place of burial
UMLAUT: An assimilatory process whereby a vowel is pronounced more like a following vocoid that is separated by one or more consonants.
